## WHAT IS PROTEUS

Proteus is a **self-evolving biological computing kernel** — a living software organism that applies Darwinian natural selection to its own codebase.

Genes are created. They compete for fitness. The weak die. The strong mutate and reproduce. When an entire population collapses, the system auto-respawns from its last viable checkpoint — stronger, with memory of what failed. After 607,157 genes processed and 293,166 kills, the kernel has never permanently died.

It is named after the Greek sea-god Proteus — the shape-shifter who could not be held, who took any form necessary to escape captivity. The name is not metaphor. It is the design spec.

**Core behaviors:**
- AST-based self-modification — the kernel rewrites its own Python source at runtime
- Golden ratio fitness scoring (`φ = 1.618034`) — fitness evaluated against the Ollin resonance function
- DNA encoding — model state serialized to FASTA format for biological-grade persistence
- Auto-respawn with checkpoint recovery — permanent death is architecturally impossible
- Peer-to-peer heartbeat mesh — nodes synchronize via SYNC-7 signal across devices
- Speciation — populations diverge into distinct evolutionary branches over time

